Summary of results and evaluation of parallel exam
The Parallel examination of the sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two audit.
In addition to the focus on "Information Exchange" in accordance with regulation (EC) no. 1798/2003 of the council and 1925/2004 of the commission, other closely related aspects were examined, for example the registration of taxable persons, tax returns and summary notifications.
In addition, the test also extended to the legal situation for cross-border passenger transport with buses and to the comparison of statistical data.
Differences in the following areas were found when comparing the systems of turnover tax administrations in the two states:
1) registration for the purposes of VAT.
While in Germany the entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, besides others, the essential criterion for registration is the overrun of the minimum prices fixed in the legislation.
In the Czech Republic, taxable persons receive only one single payment card, which they also use for intra-community transactions.
In Germany, the taxable person receives a tax number only applicable for domestic transactions for the purposes of VAT.
If the German taxable person wants to make intra-community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called UST-Idnr.
Since the different registration procedures have problems, the rules should be unified within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport with buses.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport with buses is free, but there is a claim for deduction of VAT.
In Germany, the transport of transport is the as far as the route through Germany is leading.
Efforts should be made at EC level to unify the situation in accordance with article 393 of council directive 2006/112 / EC of 28. November 2006 on the common turnover tax system (see 4.2).
3) tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic, taxable persons have to pay only for tax-free tax periods (month or quarter), taxable persons have in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Sales of VAT and to make a sales declaration after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, taxable persons in Germany have to make the vat of by electronic means.
The Introduction of the obligation to provide the electronic charge of turnover in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of Czech financial management (see 4.3).
4) summary stories.
While taxable persons in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary reports to the offices (Fä), German taxable persons have the summary notifications in the case of the clo2.
Accordingly, the information from the summary reports in the Czech Republic is available immediately after their submission.
German fä, the information from the summary reports is only available after their processing by the clo.
In order to combat the turnover tax, updated information on intra-community transactions is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the date of turnover and the update of the Mia data.
This would allow for a timely examination of taxation in the member state of the acquirer (see 4.4), but only when all EC member states introduce the same deadlines.
5) International Exchange of information in the field of VAT.
In the case of incoming request for information, Czech clo monitors compliance with the months.
The German clo does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has done a significantly lower percentage of the request for information within the specified deadline
Due to these problems, the brh recommended to German clo a constant monitoring of the deadlines (see 4.6).
6) Risk Management.
Each of the two member states will be able to develop their own risk (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The nku and the brh point out that an effective rms can not be developed by a member state alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of a rms must be exchanged and implemented in all EC member states. Otherwise, scammers will choose the member state with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
In the framework of the cooperation, the two audit examined selected cases of intra-community transactions realized between Czech and German tax authorities.
Of this, 31 cases were checked together by using the legal possibilities of clo, where there was doubts about the correct taxation or the suspicion of turnover.
