Cross-border passenger transport with bus
The statutory regulations in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of § 70 of law no. In 235/2004, since 1. May 2004, the transport of passengers between the individual member states and between the member states and third countries in the Czech Republic is exempt from VAT and there is a claim for deduction of VAT.
The exemption from VAT is also valid when the transport of persons registered in other member states as taxable persons or by foreigners who are taxable in the domestic market are carried out.
The return journey is considered a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not practice any other economic activity than the cross-border passenger transport with buses, they are not allowed to register in the Czech Republic as a public transport service.
Cross-border passenger transport was in the Czech Republic due to the law on the accession of the Czech Republic Appendix No. V, Chapter 5 (1) (b) excluded from the VAT. The cited position is in the wording:
" for the purpose of applying article 28 (3) (b) of directive 77/388 / EEC, the Czech Republic May, in accordance with point 17 of annex f to the directive, maintain the exemption for cross-border passenger transport either as long as until the requirement of article 28 (4) of the directive is fulfilled or as long as the same tax exemption is applied by any of the current member states."
The statutory regulations in Germany
In accordance with article 46 of council directive 2006/112 / EC of 28. November 2006, as it has been implemented in Germany by § 3 B (1) Ustg, a transport is carried out there, where the transport will be carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between a domestic and a cross-border passenger transport.
Only the part of the transport that is attributable to the domestic market is taxable in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-Resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxable person is transported by Germany, the part of the transport in Germany is considered as a taxable transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-Resident Entrepreneur has to report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent fa.
This register him for tax purposes (Comparisons 4.1.2) and gives a special certificate for everyone in the registration of the taxable person.
