The (UCR) took a contract from a Danish company (Udk) for the production of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria on behalf, to the risk and invoice of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient own sales costs, the Danish company gave a part of the order to a German taxable person (ude) in Germany.
The following figure represents the contractual relationships and the transport route of wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these shops must be determined as described below:
- the Danish company (Udk) sent the wind turbines in its name, at its risk and for its own invoice for assembly to Austria.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of wind turbines is controlled in Austria.
- because the forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (Udk) and the latter made transport in its own name, at its own risk and for its own invoice, it is place of delivery of the German sub-Entrepreneur (ude) where the transport has begun, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines have been delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as taxable in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-Entrepreneur (ude), as the EC has been registered for the-member state for which the delivery was intended to be a different than the state of the Czech unternehmens19.
Accordingly, the delivery is properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its payment documents.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) is also aimed at the place where the transport has begun.
However, some of the wind turbines have been transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- the delivery of wind turbines produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- the delivery of the rest of the wind turbines produced in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria as well as intra-community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The brh found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-community deliveries in its German tax returns or in its zm delivered to the german clo.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-community deliveries uniformly as intra-community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The nku found that (UCR) did not report intra-community deliveries to Austria, but intra-community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-community acquisitions in Austria, the cooperation of at least four financial institutions (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although there are no signs of tax fraud or tax evasion
